definition.value: A specifically dependent continuant  that inheres in continuant  entities and are not exhibited in full at every time in which it inheres in an entity or group of entities. The exhibition or actualization of a realizable entity is a particular manifestation, functioning or process that occurs under certain circumstances.

A realizable entity  the manifestation of which brings about some result or end that is not essential to a continuant  in virtue of the kind of thing that it is but that can be served or participated in by that kind of continuant  in some kinds of natural, social or institutional contexts.
An independent continuant that is spatially extended whose identity is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.
A racemate comprising equal amounts of (R)- and (S)-warfarin. Extensively used as both an anticoagulant drug and as a pesticide against rats and mice.

A member of the class of 1-benzothiophenes that is 1-benzothiophene in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by a 1-[carbamoyl(hydroxy)amino]ethyl group. A selective 5-lipoxygenase inhibitor, it inhibits the formation of leukotrienes LTB4, LTC4, LDT4, and LTE4. It is used for the management of chronic asthma.
A piperazine compound having 1,2-benzothiazol-3-yl- and 2-(6-chloro-1,3-dihydro-2-oxindol-5-yl)ethyl substituents attached to the nitrogen atoms.
A 1,2-benzoxazole compound having a sulfamoylmethyl substituent at the 3-position.
Elementary particle not affected by the strong force having a spin 1/2, a negative elementary charge and a rest mass of 0.000548579903(13) u, or 0.51099906(15) MeV.
The (S)-enantiomer of carnitine.
A glycerophosphocholine having an unspecified O-acyl substituent at the 1-position of the glycerol fragment.
A quinazoline compound having a (3-ethynylphenyl)amino group at the 4-position and two 2-methoxyethoxy groups at the 6- and 7-positions.
A glycerophosphocholine having an unspecified acyl group attached at the 2-position.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

1,4-Dihydro-2H-3,1-benzoxazin-2-one substituted at the 4 position by cyclopropylethynyl and trifluoromethyl groups (S configuration) and at the 6 position by chlorine. A non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor with activity against HIV, it is used with other antiretrovirals for combination therapy of HIV infection.
The conjugate base of gamma-amino-beta-hydroxybutyric acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.

Any member of a group of fat-soluble retinoids produced via metabolism of provitamin A carotenoids that exhibit biological activity against vitamin A deficiency. Vitamin A is involved in immune function, vision, reproduction, and cellular communication.
Any steroid substituted by a formyl group.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Mycoplasma genitalium.
A steroid compound with a structure based on a 27-carbon (cholestane) skeleton.
A steroid compound with a structure based on a 19-carbon (androstane) skeleton.
An icosanoid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of any hydroxyicosatetraenoic acid.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any octadecanoid.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid.
An octadecanoid anion anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hydroperoxyoctadecadienoic acid.
Any monounsaturated fatty acid anion carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid anion carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
A class of carbonyl compound encompassing dicarboxylic acids and any derivatives obtained by substitution of either one or both of the carboxy hydrogens.
A molecular entity that can undergo reduction by the gain of hydrogen atom(s).
A cholesterol ester in which the acyl group contains 20 carbons and 5 double bonds.
An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfonate group of any fatty acid-taurine conjugate; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty acid-taurine conjugate obtained by deprotonation of the sulfonate group of N-stearoyltaurine; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion resulting from the addition of a proton to the piperazine nitrogen that is not attached to the pyrimidinyl group. The major species at pH 7.3.
Any member of the class of benzoquinones that is 1,4-benzoquinone or its C-substituted derivatives.
A naphthoquinone in which the oxo groups of the quinone moiety are at positions 1 and 4 of the parent naphthalene ring.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of hyaluronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is 3-methylbut-2-enoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A primary amine that is isopropylamine in which a hydrogen attached to one of the methyl groups has been replaced by a phenyl group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the secondary amino function of phenylephrine.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the secondary amino function of methamphetamine.
A citrate anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups as well as the hydroxy group of citric acid.
